# Solution & folder layout

```text
src/
|-- CSharpModulith.Shared/                    # Shared kernel (class library)
|-- CSharpModulith.Capability.<CapabilityName>/  # One class library per capability
|-- CSharpModulith.Host/                      # ASP.NET Core host: composition root, HTTP pipeline
|-- CSharpModulith.AppHost/                   # .NET Aspire app host (orchestration)
|-- CSharpModulith.ServiceDefaults/           # Shared service defaults (OpenTelemetry, health, etc.)
```

- **Capabilities** live in `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<CapabilityName>/` (one `.csproj` per capability).
- **Shared kernel** lives in `src/CSharpModulith.Shared/`.
- **Host**, **AppHost**, and **ServiceDefaults** are composition and platform; they are **not** business capabilities.

Capability tests: `tests/CSharpModulith.Capability.<CapabilityName>.Tests/` (see **Test Folder Setup** below).

# Physical paths vs root namespaces

- **Physical project / folder**: `CSharpModulith.Shared`, `CSharpModulith.Capability.<CapabilityName>` (matches `.csproj` names under `src/`).
- **Default root namespace** (set in each `.csproj` via `RootNamespace`):
  - Shared: `App.Shared`
  - Capability: `App.Capability.<CapabilityName>`
- Inner folders extend the root namespace (e.g. `Application` ŌåÆ `App.Capability.Order.Application`). Do **not** use `CSharpModulith.Capability.Order` as the C# namespace unless you deliberately change `RootNamespace`.

# Modules

- Every business capability is a separate project under `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<CapabilityName>/`.
- Capability projects reference `CSharpModulith.Shared` when they need shared types.

## Module base types

At the capability project root (or a documented single folder), keep module-wide types discoverable:

```text
src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/
|-- <Name>Exception.cs              # Module base exception
|-- <Name>Failure.cs                # Error codes / failure taxonomy
|-- <Name>Config.cs                 # Module-specific configuration (optional)
```

# Facades

- Facade **contracts** belong in `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<moduleName>/Application/`, named `<Name>FacadeInterface` (or `<Name>Facade` if you use a concrete entry type). Do **not** use the `I` prefix for interfaces; use an `Interface` suffix instead.
- Facade methods follow [facade-design.mdc](facade-design.mdc) (Requests/Responses, primitives, `WithSuccess` / `WithFailure` patterns).
- You MUST NOT catch exceptions in facades unless explicitly specified.

# Layers

## Application layer

- Each capability project MUST have **Application**, **Domain**, and **Infrastructure** folders (Presentation is optional until you expose HTTP/UI from the capability).
- A facade MAY use use-case input/result types when it only delegates to a use case.
- A facade method that does **not** delegate to a use case MUST use Request/Response types from `Application/Requests` and `Application/Responses` (see facade-design).
- **Queries**: subfolders named after the read data they represent (views).
- Read-repository interfaces: `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<moduleName>/Application/Repositories/`.
- Folders inside the application layer SHOULD be plural where they denote collections of things (`UseCases`, `Repositories`, ŌĆ”).
- The application layer MUST NOT take unnecessary dependencies on infrastructure; keep references minimal. Domain MUST remain free of infrastructure.
- You MUST NOT catch exceptions in use cases unless explicitly specified.
- Bridge interfaces to other capabilities: `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<moduleName>/Application/Bridges/`.

### Application layer folder structure

```text
src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/
|-- Application/
|   |-- UseCases/
|   |   |-- <UCName>/
|   |   |   |-- <UCName>.cs
|   |   |   |-- <UCName>Input.cs
|   |   |   |-- <UCName>Result.cs
|   |-- Repositories/
|   |   |-- <Name>ReadRepositoryInterface.cs
|   |-- Queries/
|   |   |-- <QueryName>/
|   |   |   |-- <QueryName>.cs
|   |-- IntegrationEventHandlers/
|   |-- DomainEventHandlers/
|   |-- Jobs/
|   |   |-- <JobName>Handler.cs
|   |   |-- <JobName>Job.cs
|   |-- Bridges/
|   |   |-- <ExtName>BridgeInterface.cs
|   |-- Services/
|   |-- Requests/
|   |-- Responses/
|   |-- <Name>FacadeInterface.cs
|   |-- <Name>ApplicationException.cs
```

## Domain layer

- Domain events: `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<moduleName>/Domain/Model/<Aggregate>/Events/`.
- Use DDD tactical patterns in the Domain layer.
- Aggregates, value objects, and entities: `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<moduleName>/Domain/Model/<Aggregate>/`.
  - One aggregate root per aggregate folder.
  - Aggregates must not share domain objects across aggregate boundaries (reference other aggregates by id only).
- An aggregate has an ID type named `<Aggregate>Id` (e.g. `OrderId`).
  - Prefer immutable ID types with a clear factory (e.g. `static OrderId From(string value)`) and stable string representation.
- Prefer a static factory (e.g. `Create`) for construction unless the ubiquitous language suggests another name.
- The domain layer MUST NOT depend on infrastructure or host frameworks.
- You MUST NOT catch exceptions in the domain layer unless explicitly specified.

### Domain assembly marker (ArchUnitNET)

- Each capability that participates in solution-wide architecture rules MUST include an empty static type `<Name>DomainMarker` under `Domain/` (e.g. `TodosDomainMarker` in `App.Capability.Todos.Domain`).
- **Purpose:** [ArchUnitNET](https://github.com/TNG/ArchUnitNET) loads compiled assemblies via `typeof(<Name>DomainMarker).Assembly`. The test project references `tests/CSharpModulith.Architecture.Tests/CapabilityLayerArchitectureTests.cs`, which registers those assemblies to enforce layer rules (domain vs application vs infrastructure vs presentation).
- The marker is **not** application logic. Document it with an XML `<summary>` explaining the ArchUnit anchor (avoid tying tests to arbitrary domain types that may move).
- When you add a capability (or split domain into its own assembly), add `<Name>DomainMarker.cs` and register `typeof(<Name>DomainMarker).Assembly` in `CapabilityLayerArchitectureTests` alongside the other capabilities.

### Domain layer folder structure

```text
src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/
|-- Domain/
|   |-- <Name>DomainMarker.cs       # empty; ArchUnitNET assembly anchor (see ŌĆ£Domain assembly markerŌĆØ)
|   |-- Model/
|   |   |-- <Aggregate>/
|   |   |   |-- Events/
|   |   |   |-- <Entity>.cs
|   |   |   |-- <ValueObject>.cs
|   |-- Services/
|   |-- Repositories/
|   |   |-- <Name>WriteRepositoryInterface.cs
```

## Infrastructure layer

- Repository implementations implement interfaces declared in:
  - `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/Application/Repositories/` (reads), and/or
  - `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/Domain/Repositories/` (writes), per your moduleŌĆÖs split.
- Place adapters under `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/Infrastructure/Persistence/<Technology>/` (e.g. `EfCore`, `Dapper`) and related concerns (`Message/`, `Bridges/`, ŌĆ”).
- **Persistence:** Follow [aggregate-persistence.mdc](aggregate-persistence.mdc) and [read-models.mdc](read-models.mdc) for mapping and repository shape; keep aggregate mapping out of inline repository spaghetti.

### Infrastructure layer folder structure

```text
src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/
|-- Infrastructure/
|   |-- Persistence/
|   |   |-- <Technology>/
|   |   |-- Schema/
|   |-- Dependencies/
|   |-- Message/
|   |-- Email/
|   |-- Bridges/
|   |   |-- <OtherModuleName>Bridge.cs
|-- Presentation/
```

## Presentation layer

- Presentation maps use-case results to HTTP, CLI, or other delivery mechanisms.
- **Authorization:** enforce authentication/authorization in the ASP.NET Core pipeline (middleware, authorization policies, filters)ŌĆönot ad-hoc checks scattered through mapping code. Capability `Presentation` types stay thin.
- HTTP endpoints MAY be registered from `CSharpModulith.Host` (minimal APIs) and/or from types under `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<moduleName>/Presentation/` (e.g. extension methods that map routes). Prefer one clear pattern per API surface.
- Keep **one primary operation per endpoint** (one use case or one query) to preserve clear boundaries.
- The presentation layer lives under `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<moduleName>/Presentation/`.
- Use subfolders per surface, for example:
  - `Presentation/<Surface>/ViewModels/` ŌĆö response shapes
  - `Presentation/<Surface>/Mappers/` ŌĆö mapping to view models
  - `Presentation/<Surface>/Validators/` or FluentValidation ŌĆö input validation
  - `Presentation/<Surface>/Requests/` ŌĆö request DTOs
- OpenAPI: module or host-owned YAML under `openapi/` or next to the API project, per [openapi.mdc](openapi.mdc).
- You MUST NOT catch exceptions in endpoint handlers unless explicitly specified; rely on centralized exception handling (see [http-api-controller-exceptions.mdc](http-api-controller-exceptions.mdc)).
- Validation failures SHOULD produce **422** with a problem-details body where the API follows [api-conventions.mdc](api-conventions.mdc).
- Successful **DELETE** SHOULD be idempotent; **204 No Content** with an empty body is appropriate when the resource is gone.

### Presentation layer folder structure

```text
src/CSharpModulith.Capability.<Name>/
|-- Presentation/
|   |-- CommandLine/
|   |   |-- ConsoleCommands/
|   |   |-- ViewModels/
|   |   |-- ViewMappers/
|   |-- Http/                        # or FrontendApi / BackendApi if you split surfaces
|   |   |-- Endpoints/               # optional: route registration helpers
|   |   |-- Requests/
|   |   |-- ViewModels/
|   |   |-- Mappers/
|   |-- <Name>PresentationException.cs
```

## Test Folder Setup

Tests live under `tests/` in projects whose names mirror the production projects under `src/`.

- **Naming**: Use the same `CSharpModulith.*` root as the code under test, append **`.Tests`** to the project folder name (e.g. `src/CSharpModulith.Capability.Todos/` ŌåÆ `tests/CSharpModulith.Capability.Todos.Tests/`; `src/CSharpModulith.Shared/` ŌåÆ `tests/CSharpModulith.Shared.Tests/`). Cross-cutting architecture rules use `tests/CSharpModulith.Architecture.Tests/`.
- **Mirroring (mandatory)**: Inside a test project, **folder paths must mirror the actual structure** of the project under test in `src/`. Same top-level layers (`Application`, `Domain`, `Infrastructure`, `Presentation`, ŌĆ”) and the **same subfolders** as the production tree (e.g. `Application/UseCases/<UseCase>/`, `Domain/Model/<Aggregate>/`). A test file belongs in the folder that matches the type it exercises. Do not use a flat test root or ad-hoc folders when production code is organized in layers.
- **Test-only folders**: Helpers with **no** production counterpart (e.g. in-memory DB, `WebApplicationFactory`, fakes shared by many tests) live under a **single** root folder in the test project, e.g. `TestInfrastructure/` or `Support/`. Do **not** use `Common/` or other names that could be confused with production layout unless `src/` has the same folder.
- **Namespaces**: Mirror production namespaces by inserting **`.Tests`** after the capability/shared segmentŌĆöe.g. production `App.Capability.Todos.Application` ŌåÆ tests `App.Capability.Todos.Tests.Application`; production `App.Shared.Application` ŌåÆ `App.Shared.Tests.Application`. Folder path and namespace stay aligned.

# Shared kernel

- The shared kernel is project `src/CSharpModulith.Shared/` with root namespace `App.Shared`.
- Use it for cross-cutting types and abstractions that truly belong in the kernelŌĆönot as a dump for capability-specific logic.
